post_text:
Today marks the conclusion of a challenging academic year. Thank you to the students, parents, and faculty for all of your hard work, dedication, and strength over the past three months. Like a family, we made it through the challenges together. Even though graduation will not be held tonight, please know, seniors, that we are all so proud of your accomplishments and we are excited to see what the next chapter holds for you. We will see you on July 11, 2020 at Whitaker Center where you will receive your diploma and officially become a CASA alum! Stay tuned for more details.

Planning for the fall is already underway, and I assure you that we are working hard to develop an option that will keep our students and staff safe, while continuing to provide meaningful and engaging instruction. Thank you for your continued support! -Tim Wendling

post_text: CASA students, Jake and Robert Myers, are making some awesome music this Memorial Day weekend. Like their page, Pyxus Music, and check out more of their amazing talent!
shared_text:
Pyxus Music
May 23 at 6:17 PM ·

Seemed an appropriate song to share this Memorial Day weekend. A song about war and sacrifice from a beautiful place in Eastern Tennessee/Western N.C, not too far from our birthplace.

Pyxus Music covers the Kruger Brothers song Harder Than Steel, one of the many songs of theirs that we love. Recorded from our own little spot on the mountain at the northern tip of the Blue Ridge Mountain range in Pennsylvania.

Thank you to those military members who ensure our freedom. Especially thinking of our special family member, Captain Mark Garner In loving memory of a true American hero, US Army Capt Mark Garner, who gave all.

#pyxusmusic #MemorialDay2020 #acousticmusic #blueridgemountains #folkmusic #brotherharmony #krugerbrothers #folk #acoustic #vocals #sing

post_text:
CASA's expansion project begins next week!

It is with great excitement that we get to share with you the news of CASA's expansion into a brand new academic wing on the third floor of Strawberry Square. The new space will house all of our academic classrooms, a science lab, and new administrative offices. These improvements will allow CASA to support additional STEAM learning opportunities as well as sustain our academic needs well into the future.

The CASA Charter School Foundation is raising $1.7 million to support the lease and renovation of the additional space. We will need parent and community support during our fundraising effort. If you are able to help CASA expand and improve its new home in downtown Harrisburg, please visit www.CASAfound.org.

Our new space is set to be completed by August 2020, prior to the start of the 2020-2021 school year.

post_text:
Congratulations to CASA Senior of the Month for May, Greta Diehl!

Greta is a theatre student who has been attending CASA since 9th grade. She comes to CASA from Central Dauphin School District.

At CASA, Greta has been a cast member of the fall play, the spring musical, and the spring play. Outside of CASA, she takes dance classes and spends time with her family and friends.

Greta’s favorite CASA memory is when the art classes go on the CASA Walk in the fall, because she loves to see the leaves changing all around the Capitol building and finds it very peaceful. Her favorite artistic piece she created at CASA was the theatre’s mid-year performance during her junior year.

In the future, Greta will be attending HACC to major in Psychology and minor in Criminal Justice.

Greta says that CASA has taught her to be herself and to always be creative, no matter what. She would like to thank everyone at CASA and says, “Every year I grew and you all helped me. I really appreciate that, and am going to miss CASA so much!”

Congratulations, Greta!

post_text:
Congratulations to CASA Senior of the Month for April, Genevieve Ehrman!

Genevieve is a visual art student who has been attending CASA since 10th grade. She comes to CASA from Lebanon SD.

At CASA, Genevieve is an active member of our French Club and Mural Club.

Genevieve’s favorite CASA memory is junior year’s CASALive! production. Her favorite artistic piece she created at CASA was the larger than life puppets personifying Ethos, Pathos, and Logos for last year’s CASALive! production.

In the future, Genevieve will be attending Tyler School of Art at Temple University, majoring in sculpture with a concentration in entrepreneurship.

Genevieve says that CASA has impacted her by changing the entire course of her life. She says, “I would not have been able to find my creative path anywhere else.” She would like to thank everyone at CASA and says, “You have no idea what this school has done for me. Thank you!”

You are the leaders of our CASA community and we miss you dearly. You inspire, you excel, and you persevere. We know this is not how any of you envisioned your last year in high school. Good Morning: Governor Wolf announced this morning that all Pennsylvania schools will be closed for the remainder of the academic school year. We know that this is the best decision for the health of all Pennsylvanians, however, as educators, we are heartbroken. We will continue moving forward with our Continuity of Education plan to keep students engaged in learning throughout the rest of the school year. -Tim Wendling, CEO/Principal

This afternoon, Governor Wolf ordered all K-12 schools to be closed for 10 business days beginning on Monday, March 16 through Friday, March 27. The Wolf Administration will continue to monitor COVID-19 in the commonwealth and at the end of 10 days will reevaluate and decide whether continued closure is needed.

A follow up email to parents will be sent over the weekend with more detailed information.

During this time, all classes, rehearsals, clubs, and activities at CASA are cancelled.

Thank you for your cooperation and understanding as we work to evaluate the situation and develop our next steps.

-Tim Wendling, CEO/Principal

**UPDATE 3/13/2020

Good Morning,
After receiving guidance from the PA Department of Health, PA Department of Education, and Governor Wolf, CASA's production of, "FAME" will be cancelled tonight and Saturday night. The ticketing website is working on providing refunds to patrons who purchased tickets. Pennsylvania's Secretary of Education held a webinar this morning reiterating that the PA Department of Education is continuously monitoring the COVID-19 situation across the state, but at this time, they are not recommending state-wide school closures. At CASA, we will continue to stress appropriate hand-washing and health habits. If your child is showing symptoms of illness, please keep them home and contact the school office AND our school nurse, Ann Stillwater. I will continue to update our students, staff, and families as new information becomes available. We are reviewing our pandemic plan so we are prepared if we have an outbreak in our school or community. For more resources, you can visit education.pa.gov. Thank you.

-Tim Wendling, CEO/Principal

post_text:
We are excited to welcome Mr. Adam Shickley to the CASA family! Beginning March 2, 2020, Mr. Shickley will take the role as CASA's second Special Education teacher. Below is a note from Mr. Shickley:

"I am really excited to join the CASA team. Since I started as a school based probation officer in 2004, I have always wanted to work in unique and varied teaching environments. I worked in various school settings and multiple non-traditional educational settings. My first teaching experience was at a private school with a large emphasis on experiential learning. It taught me that some students learn better getting their hands on their education. During the last six school years, I have worked for the Capital Area Intermediate Unit. I taught in many varied situations, autism support, emotional support, and in mental health programming. I've worked as a teacher and case manager for my entire career. I am looking forward to bringing my unique experiences to CASA Charter School and I can't wait to help the students succeed."

post_text:
We are excited to welcome Mrs. Maria Thiaw to the CASA family! Beginning March 2, 2020 she will be the Creative Writing teacher. Below is a note from Mrs. Thiaw:

"I can't wait to share my passion for the literary arts with the creative writers at CASA! Like many of you, my love of language started at a young age and through experiences with amazing mentors I've grown from spoken word artist and slam poet to published author and playwright. In 2009 I earned my MFA in Creative Writing from Goddard College. I taught English and Communication at the college level for 16 years. I also have experience with several different types of professional writing that can help you become a working artist and not a starving one! So if that sounds 'write' to you, let's create the writing life you've been dreaming about!"

post_text:
It is with great excitement that we get to share with you the news of CASA's expansion into a brand new academic wing on the third floor of Strawberry Square. The new space will house all of our academic classrooms, a science lab, and new administrative offices. These improvements will allow CASA to support additional STEAM learning opportunities as well as sustain our academic needs well into the future.

The CASA Charter School Foundation is raising $1.6 million to support the lease and renovation of the additional space. We will need parent and community support during our fundraising effort. If you are able to help CASA expand and improve its new home in downtown Harrisburg, please visit www.CASAfound.org.

Our new space is set to be completed by August 2020, prior to the start of the 2020-2021 school year.

As always, thanks for your continued support!

post_text:
Congratulations to CASA Senior of the Month for January, 2020, Azzlynn Patrick!

Azzlynn is a visual art student who has been attending CASA since 9th grade. She comes to CASA from Cumberland Valley SD.

At CASA, Azzlynn was an active member of our technical crew for last year’s spring musical, Hair, and the fall plays, The Crucible and The Complete Works of Shakespeare. Outside of CASA, she is a member of the Student Conservation Association, shows her work at various local art galleries, and works part-time at Michael’s Crafts and in the summer for the DCNR’s PA Outdoor Corps.

Azzlynn’s favorite CASA memories are her daily trips to visit Mrs. Chambers. Her favorite artistic piece she created at CASA is titled, “Mom Made Banana Pancakes.”

In the future, Azzlynn plans on pursuing a career in Art Therapy.

Azzlynn says that CASA has impacted her life by giving her confidence to “become a leader amongst my peers and an advocate for my education.”

Congratulations, Azzlynn!

post_text:
CASA is excited to present "The Bad Seed" at Gamut Theatre this Thursday and Friday at 7:00 p.m. Tickets are on sale at www.casa-arts.org. Get yours today!

"The Bad Seed" is a 1954 play by American playwright Maxwell Anderson. The play focuses on the seemingly perfect little girl Rhoda Penmark, who is able to charm her way into getting just about anything she wants. Anything, except a highly coveted penmanship medal that her teacher has awarded to Claude Daigle, one of Rhoda's classmates. During a school outing near the shore, Claude goes missing and it is soon discovered that Claude has drowned near a pier. Rhoda's mother, Christine, begins to suspect that Rhoda had something to do with the boy's death when she finds Claude's penmanship medal hidden in Rhoda's room.... You must attend CASA's production of "The Bad Seed" to see what happens next! See you at the show!

post_text:
Garden of Earthly Delights
Featuring 11-12th Grade Visual Artists
November 7th, 2019
Opening Reception: 6:00 - 7:30 PM

The 11th-12th Grade Visual Art Class at Capital Area School for the Arts Charter School (CASA) is proud to present, Garden of Earthly Delights:

Hieronymus Bosch's, The Garden of Earthly Delights, stands as one of the greatest masterpieces of the Renaissance. The triptych is thought to be a warning, but has been subject to scrutiny by critics and historians. In our exhibition, Garden of Earthly Delights, twenty artists have collaborated to create a cohesive body of work that simultaneously borrows and builds on Bosch’s vivid imagery and complexity of symbolic meaning. The works in this exhibition testify to the continuing relevance of Bosch’s appetite for discovery and the fall of man. Join us from 6:00 to 7:30 PM on November 7th for the opening reception.

Based out of New York City, Ailey II is universally renowned for merging the spirit and energy of the country’s best young dance talent with the passion and creative vision of today’s most outstanding emerging choreographers. CASA students had the opportunity to participate in a class, learn choreography from the Ailey II repertory, and participate in a Q & A session with the dancers. It was a wonderful experience for all involved!

post_text:
Congratulations to CASA Senior of the Month for October, Helen Hamilton!

She is a visual art student who has been attending CASA since 9th grade.

At CASA, Helen is an active member of Student Council, National Honor Society, and French Club. She also submits her work to Scholastic’s Art and Writing Competitions. Outside of CASA, she tutors individuals in math, works part-time at Hanna’s Ice Cream Shoppe, and participates in the Vickie’s Angel Walk.

Her favorite artistic piece she created at CASA is the oil pastel entitled, Trash.

In the future, Helen would like to attend a research school to major in Biochemistry and minor in Public Health or Epidemiology. She hopes to someday pursue a career as a researcher of large-scale epidemics and diseases.

Helen says that CASA has impacted her life by providing her with collaborative and artistic skills. She would like to thank her friend, Nadia El-Mourli, who has inspired her to do her best and who makes her day better every morning during Miss Flood’s first period.

Congratulations, Helen!

Market Square Concerts
October 9, 2019 at 11:47 AM ·

Our 2019-20 season’s “Soundscape” educational outreach program continued yesterday at Whitaker Center for Science and the Arts with a performance of Fairy Tales set to music by Daniel Dorff, Kile Smith, and Gwyneth Walker: Composer. The performers were our director, Peter Sirotin, Ai-Lin Hsieh, as well as narrators, Greta Diehl and Noah Smull, both are students at the Capital Area School for the Arts Charter School (CASA).

MSC is grateful to Highmark Blue Shield, McInroy-Sheffer People Trust, as well as the "Whitaker Center Lois Lehrman Grass Performing Arts Fund: Youth Performing Arts Program Partnership Grant" for the generous support of Soundscape!

The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society's Light The Night Walk brings light to the darkness of cancer by funding lifesaving research and support for people battling cancer. Family, friends and co-workers gather together to celebrate, honor or remember those touched by cancer. Registration is free, but walkers are encouraged to raise funds to support the mission. These efforts culminate in inspirational, memorable evening experiences filled with music, food trucks, fireworks and empowering ceremonies honoring survivors and remembering those we have lost.

Ms. Flood is participating on behalf of CASA and has formed a walking team: CASA4Cures. If you are interested in joining the the team for the walk and/or donating to the cause, please visit the team website at: https://pages.lls.org/ltn/cpa/Harrisbg19/CASA4Cures

post_text:
In CASA's underclassmen Sculptural Doppelgänger Unit, Visual Art students experimented with sculptural head-wear. Students first thought about their second selves and alter egos. They challenged themselves to think about unique manipulation of materials and sculptural shapes. By the end of this unit, students learned from start to finish the process of creating and modeling wearable art.

Leading Photographer: Rosie Gnazzo

post_text:
Visual Art Gallery
TONIGHT @ Whitaker Center Lobby
Beginning at 5:30 prior to CASALive!

In addition to the CASALive! theme of 'Revolutions,' the Upperclassmen Visual Art class created a gallery show in the lobby of The Whitaker Center entitled, 'Visions.' This gallery focuses on the idea of change and how change comes about. Many of the pieces in 'Visions' center around storytelling and the constant strive for utopia, while others focus on dreams and more literal visions. In all, it expresses the lighter side of revolution which can often be overlooked.

The gallery explores a variety of different mediums, including fabric and cotton, paper cut-outs, and sculpture, as a way to express personal and artistic values. At the same time, the group made the show visually consistent by using similar colors and patterns that are representative of a vision.

'Visions' acts as an introduction for 'Revolutions,' but displays the outcome of one; in a way, we come full circle.

We hope you enjoy!

Nathan is a music student who has been attending CASA since 9th grade. He comes to CASA from West Shore School District.

At CASA, Nathan participates in the Music Theory Club. Outside of CASA, he participates in guitar lessons at the Pollock Center.

In the future, Nathan will be interning at Rock Lititz Studio and plans to attend Berklee College of Music.

Nathan says that CASA has impacted his life by helping him find his family and become happy with himself and his life. He says, “You’ve all helped me spread love through my music and that love has spread more love like a domino effect. For that, I am grateful.”

Congratulations, Nathan!

post_text: In CASA's underclassmen Visual Art Mural Unit, students created masking tape murals throughout CASA's halls to express what they have learned about each other as a class community. To gain some inspiration for this unit, students explored contemporary and local murals in Harrisburg. After discussing contemporary street art, we looked at tape art as an alternative method to the widespread use of spray cans in the urban art scene. Along with the restriction of masking tape, students challenged themselves to develop unique symbols, surrealistic imagery, innovative patterns, and cohesive compositions. By the end of this unit, students learned not only the process of creating large scale site-specific artwork, but also the different facets of our community.

post_text:
Congratulations to CASA Senior of the Month for April, Jordan Allen!

Jordi is a dance student who has been attending CASA since 9th grade. She comes to CASA from Northern York SD. At CASA, Jordi participates in the National Honor Society for Dance Arts. Outside of CASA, she is an instructor for the Northern York Dance Team, is a member of the Northern York High School Color Guard, and is a choreographer for Northern York Middle School’s musicals.

Jordi has too many favorite memories at CASA to count. Her favorite artistic pieces she created were her duet, “Earth,” and a group piece, “Harmony."

In the future, Jordi will be attending Slippery Rock University and wants to become a professional choreographer.

Jordi says that CASA has impacted her life by teaching her to be more confident and to truly accept herself. She would like to thank Mrs. Battista for believing in her passion and she is thankful to her friends for helping her get through the tough times.

Congratulations, Jordi!

post_text: CASA Student Council is hosting two events in the coming weeks. post_text:
Congratulations to Grace Harrison! She is a CASA Senior of the Month for January! Great job, Grace!

Grace is a visual art student who has been attending CASA since 9th grade. She comes to CASA from West Perry SD.

At CASA, Grace takes a variety of courses, and has created art pieces for various scenes for CASA’s Integrated Arts. Outside of CASA, Grace actively participates in dance classes.

Grace said two of her favorite memories at CASA were participating in CASALive! and travelling to Europe with our school. Her favorite artistic piece she created at CASA was the six people she painted with mylar over them. That piece is currently featured in the front staircase at CASA.

In the future, Grace would like to attend Penn State University to pursue a Bachelor’s Degree, and possibly a Master’s Degree.

Grace says that CASA has impacted her life in a profound way. She says, “I was struggling mentally before I came here, and I can truthfully say that CASA saved my life!” She thanks those who make CASA possible.
